it may be due to the same issue https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/2814
which was recently fixed in master with
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/2833
can you confirm if your model has topK which requires int64 type support?
There's a followup PR that makes it easy to add more types here - https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/2842

@jywu-msft @pranavsharma  thanks for your response. From onnx documentation:

```
Type Constraints
T : tensor(uint8), tensor(uint16), tensor(uint32), tensor(uint64), tensor(int8), tensor(int16), tensor(int32), tensor(int64), tensor(float16), tensor(float), tensor(double)
```

https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/Operators.md#TopK

It should support input with type int64.

Actually, what surprise me is that I remmber I successfully forwarded such as likely model with TopK node. But now it fails, so strange.
Which opset are you using? Can you share the model? I just updated topk to support int64_t for opset 11 only.

body:
The following model reproduces the error with onnxruntime 1.1.2.

https://drive.google.com/file/d/1Vgj_evFx2mvUBIf3713OpKWnifpX7HlV/view?usp=drivesdk
(md5sum is `c60f5519f3a6a8e0fc5a7c98641179c1`)

I produced it with the below PyTorch 1.4.0 code, exporting to opset 11. I ran `onnx.checker.check_model` and did no see any errors (using onnx 1.6.0).

```python
import torch
import torch.nn as nn

class SortNet(nn.Module):
    
    def forward(self, X):
        values, indices = X.sort(descending=True)
        return indices

net = SortNet()
X = torch.arange(10)

torch.onnx.export(
    net,
    X,
    'sort.onnx',
    export_params=True,
    do_constant_folding=True,
    opset_version=11,
    input_names=['input'],
    output_names=['output'],
    dynamic_axes={
        'input': {0: 'batch'},
        'output': {0: 'batch'},
    },
    verbose=True
)
```
